@Node WhatIsABBS "What is a BBS ?"

  What Is A BBS ?
  ===============

    A BBS (Bulletin Board System) is where you have a computer which acts as
    a file and message server.  Generally it sits on the end of a phone line
    and other users call it and leave messages to one another and transfer
    files to and from the BBS for the purpose of sharing with others or the
    sysop (owner) of the bbs.  You can also have a BBS on the internet where
    people from all around the world communicate to your BBS via telnet.

    HBBS Supports both, the latter only with a package called telnetd.

@EndNode

@Node Overview "Overview"

  Overview
  ========

  There is one main program with a GUI (that can be turned off/closed) that
  controls the node programs, the main programs sends messages to the node
  programs and the node program sends messages back to the main program
  depending on what is happening.

  Each node program only controls the actual serial port device and the
  order in which a user can go around the bbs system, running commands or
  doors when appropriate.

  For every option/system event the node program loads external programs.

  E.g.

  A user logs on, the node program runs a frontend door that may ask for the
  username and password, after that door is finished the control goes back to
  the node program which then runs an initial login door that may display
  ansi screens etc.  Then the node program would call a command to join the
  last conference the user was in, then it goes back to the node program
  which then loads another door to prompts the user for command, and
  depending on what the user types in that door my load other doors
  and so on.

  So EVERY SINGLE PART OF THE PROGRAM can be changed, So if you don't like
  the way the system does mail messages for instance then just change the
  associated doors that handle the mail system!  It's so configurable and
  openly designed it's just unbelievable!

@EndNode

@Node Intro "Introduction"

  Introduction
  ============

  HydraBBS is (C) 1994-1999 Dominic Clifton

  HydraBBS - A Revolutionary new BBS System to replace the ageing AmiExpress
  bulletin board software.

  The time has come for a new BBS system, /X Has been around for ages now
  and it's showing it's age.  So HBBS Will take it's place!

  You'll be AMAZED at it's power, overwhelmed by it's configurability and
  stunned by it's userfriendliness!

  HBBS has been in development since December 1994.

  Development is taking place in a few stages, first I got totally fed up with
  AmiExpress, as it's a big bag of s**t, so I just thought about writing a
  BBS System.  After all I thought,  if someone can write /X and get away
  making loads of money, why can't I ?  Then I thought "Hrm, what if I was to
  offer it as a FREE/CHEAP program that people could use and love using ?"
  So I then decided to ask loads of sysops what they hated most about /X and
  what they liked about it, and finally what else they wanted as well!  After
  compiling a big list of ideas I got round to writing some example config
  files and docs just so that I could get an idea of what people liked.
  After a few suggestions from people I finally started writing some code
  and after a time things started taking shape!

@EndNode

@Node VS "HydraBBS vs /X"

  HydraBBS vs AmiExpress
  ======================

  HydraBBS was written to surpass the ageing Amiexpress sytem, here's a few
  reason's why you as a sysop should use it instead of LamiExpress!

  * FULLY MODULAR  If you don't like something, then you can change it!
    And if you find something you can't change, e-mail me and I'll make
    it so you can change it!

  * COOL SYSTEM UTILS and DOORS,  Comes complete with all the bbs tools
    and doors you'll ever need! (FR, Wall, BulletinMaker etc. etc..)

  * Easy To Code Doors! As the system is modular it's dead easy to access data

  * Comes With a Converter to convert all your /X Icons to Text files and moves
    all your screens to the right places! to ease the changeover!

  * Can be run at the same time as /X (uses HBBS: assign rather than BBS:)
    so you can install it and test it before ditching /X totally! :-)

  * Supports ALL XPR Transfer Protocols (as well as HydraCom)

  * HBBS can be made to run without ANY sysop interactivity.  From
    autovalidation of new users to backing up and deleting old files!

  * Ever Had Modem Problems with /X ?  Bet ya have!  That's why HBBS's device
    config has the most complete set of configuration commands ever seen!

  * Small CODE (due to the Modular design) = Low Memory Overheads!

  * Written in C for maximum portability and ease of modification, and
    debugged using CyberGuard.

  * Source Code Availiable!  Yup, you heard right.  Now you can be
    100% SURE that there's NO backdoors!

  * Similar Approach to /X's config style,  only instead of millions of .info
    files everywhere you have a few text based config files.  No More editing
    bloody tooltypes!

  * Access Per Conference, at last you can give users EALL messages in set
    confs!,  All Access commands can be overridden differently in each conf!

  * Messages can have expiry dates! No more trudging through thousands of mail
    messages trying to reclaim HD space..

  * Support for sending all kinds of mail and to multiple users at the same
    time!

  * Full Support for FILE_ID!

  * Loads of smart features in the doors that you'd never find in /X!

  * Support for removable media, i.e you can set the system up so that when you
    insert a cd rom it enables certain filelists and download paths.  And when
    you take the cd-rom out it disables them again..

  * Cheap Registration.  even less if you are upgrading from *any* other BBS
    system

  And Now Some Reasons for you users to persuade your sysop to change over to
  HBBS!

  * Totally Configurable from the users point of view!

  * SuperQuick Logins!  (via terminal program scripts for term/ncomm
    (supplied!))

  * User Key Files,  No More Hassle Getting Validation on other BBS's thanks to
    this cool idea!

  * Remembers flagged files after carrier loss

  * You can select files in one conference, select Download in another and
    it remembers which files you want to d/l and from which conf.  Works with
    Conference Accounting too!

  * After uploading a load of files you can select which conf they should go in!

@EndNode

@Node QuickStart "QuickStart"

  Quickstart
  ==========

    Installing HydraBBS will not mess-up your system, nothing is installed
    anywhere else on your system, no libs, fonts, devs etc are copied AT ALL
    It runs entirly from it's own directory so you can remove it if you
    *really* want to.  Though you won't ever want to... :-)

    Anyway, here goes...

    If you're reading this then you've got as far as running the installer
    script to create an HBBS directory with a load of files and directories
    in it.

    You may notice that most of the supplied icons use TEXTVIEW and TTX as
    the default tools.  If you do not have these tools, then use MULTIVIEW
    and ED as replacements (or whatever you like)

    Open the HBBS directory within workbench

    Next, double click the Readme.1st icon to read important startup
    information!

    Now double click the "Setup" icon in the HBBS directory and a script
    will set some temporary assigns up that will be lost when you reboot.

    Have a look at the "Setup" file in a text editor to see how to get
    the assigns added to your user-startup file so they are permanent.

    (Later, take a look at Storage/Example_screens/Utopia for the screens
    that my BBS, Utopia, uses..)

    Next open HBBS:BBSGlobal in a text editor and change all the references
    of SYS: to the drive you installed HydraBBS on.  e.g. DH3:

    Save the file and go back to workbench.

    (Later, have a look at the main config files:
    HBBS:Nodes/NodeGlobal
    HBBS:Nodes/NodeX/NodeLocal
    HBBS:Nodes/NodeX/Device
    HBBS:Conferences/ConfList
    HBBS:Conferences/<confname>/ConfConfig
    HBBS:System/Data/ConfAcs/#?
    HBBS:System/#?
    pay attention to SerialDevice= in the "HBBS:Nodes/NodeX/Device" files)

    The example configs have been set up for 1 node (Node0), that doesn't
    use any "serial.device" or compatiable driver.

    Then to start up the system double click on the "CONTROL" icon.

    A loading screen will appear, followed by a requester to select a
    screenmode, pick something like 640x400x16 colours or better (or
    using a public screen) (HBBS will run on 640x200x2 colours)

    When you've selected a screen mode, the HBBS Control screen will
    appear, shortly followed by a node control panel and a node watch
    window.

    If not, check the HBBS: assign is ok, and that you have files
    in HBBS:System/Amiga/Libs, in particular HBBSCommon.library and
    HBBSNode.library.  Also check for error messages, and maybe take
    a look at hbbs:logs/#?

    To save the current screenmode and position of the Control window,
    click "Configure" then "Save"

    * Creating A Sysop Account

    Once you have started a node, go to the watch screen and press F1 to
    do a local login.

    Login as the person you want to be the sysop.

    Go through all the normal new-user stuff as you would normally until
    you get to the BBS Prompt.

    Now press F6 and see @{"On-line account editing" link HBBS:Docs/Doors/AccountEdit.Guide/ValidatingAUser} so that you can validate
    your sysop account.

    Create a file in HBBS:Access/Users/<yourhandle> with your sysop
    access settings in (e.g. UnlimitedTime=YES...)

    Now Close down HydraBBS and edit HBBS:BBSGlobal and
    HBBS:Nodes/NodeGlobal and change the SysopAccount setting to the
    handle you just used to log into the bbs.


    That's it, installation is complete!  Now read the rest of the docs
    before you ask me anything :-)


    If you want to have a look at the other example node configurations then
    edit BBSNodes in HBBS:BBSGlobal and set it to 4 instead of 1.
    Then, remove the semi-colon's in HBBS:Nodes/NodeList from the remaining
    NodeLocation and AutoStart options.  Then restart HBBS.

@EndNode




